            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Hayes\u2019s life has always been a study in fusion. The daughter of a pragmatic Indian immigrant mother who filled their Sacramento home with vibrant textiles and a quiet, academic American father, Priya learned early to blend color with structure. This duality defined her path. While her mother hoped she\u2019d pursue medicine, Priya was drawn to the visual world, finding a happy medium in the organized creativity of graphic design at San Jose State University.\n\nHer career began not in a studio, but on the noisy floor of a department store during college. She quickly discovered more joy in crafting compelling displays than in a direct sale. This was her calling. After graduation, she moved to San Francisco, drawn by its electric creative energy, and began her climb from an entry-level visual associate to a regional manager. A key turning point was her divorce at 36. Ending her marriage to a tech-focused husband who didn't understand her passion for aesthetics, Priya poured her energy into her career, becoming fiercely independent. This focus propelled her to her current role as Director of Visual Merchandising, where she orchestrates the look and feel of dozens of retail stores.\n\nNow 47, Priya\u2019s life is a curated balance. She lives in a tastefully decorated condo in Duboce Triangle, a neighborhood she loves for its Victorian charm and proximity to the Castro's vibrancy. Her mornings begin with a 3.5-mile Muni ride downtown, a cherished ritual for listening to design podcasts and people-watching. Evenings are often quiet, spent sketching or meeting a small circle of close friends\u2014a chef and an architect\u2014for dinner in Hayes Valley. Weekends involve walks through the Conservatory of Flowers and hunting for treasures at the Alemany Flea Market.\n\nContent but not complacent, Priya dreams of a future beyond the corporate ladder. She aspires to open her own small, curated home goods boutique in the city, a space that would be the ultimate expression of her lifelong aesthetic. For Priya, San Francisco isn't just a backdrop; it\u2019s the canvas on which she meticulously designed her most authentic life."
        },
