            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  At 20, she stayed late on the department store floor, long after close. Under the humming fluorescent lights, she wasn't just dressing a mannequin; she was arranging a story with silk scarves and structured wool. A sudden, quiet thrill hit her\u2014a clarity her design classes hadn't yet offered. This tangible, three-dimensional narrative was her calling. It was the moment she understood her art wasn\u2019t meant for a screen, but for the world you could walk through, cementing the true direction of her life.\n\n2.  Her first lead on a major holiday window in Union Square, age 27. She\u2019d fought for a spare, elegant design against calls for more clutter. Standing across the street in the damp evening air, she watched a couple stop, point, and talk about it for a full minute. A profound sense of belonging washed over her. This wasn't just a display; it was a conversation with the city. For the first time, she felt her unique vision\u2014that blend of color and structure\u2014was truly seen and valued.\n\n3.  The first night in her Duboce Triangle condo at 36 felt vast and quiet. Her marriage was over, its artifacts packed in boxes. Ignoring the essentials, she unwrapped a single, carved wooden bird from her father and placed it on the bare mantelpiece. The echo in the empty room wasn't lonely, but liberating. This small, deliberate act of placement was a declaration of independence\u2014the first stroke of a life she would now design entirely for herself, without apology or explanation.\n\n4.  On a foggy Muni ride downtown in her early 40s, a man in a faded leather jacket sat holding a single, perfect white orchid. The contrast\u2014the tough, worn texture against the delicate, living sculpture\u2014was a poem only she seemed to be reading. It wasn't a grand event, but it was deeply San Franciscan. This quiet, accidental arrangement of grit and grace affirmed her love for the city's uncurated beauty and the endless, fleeting stories it told to anyone paying attention.\n\n5.  Last year at the Alemany Flea Market, her hand brushed against a set of heavy, imperfect ceramic cups tucked into a dusty crate. They weren't a matched set, but they felt like a complete story. Holding their cool, textured weight, the abstract idea of her own shop became a tangible, urgent need. It wouldn't be about just selling things; it would be about this exact feeling\u2014the thrill of discovery, of curated history. That Sunday morning, her future shifted from a corporate ladder to a small, beloved storefront."
